04831nam a22006735i 9780748694228DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222015stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486942287 a10.1515/97807486942282doi  a(DE-B1597)619360  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aBP188.8.E3bH637 2020 7aHIS0090002bisacsh04a297.4096209021 aHofer, Nathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Popularisation of Sufism in Ayyubid and Mamluk Egypt, 1173-1325 /cNathan Hofer. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Studies in Classical Islamic History and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE State-sponsored Sufism: The Sufis of the Khānqāh Saʿīd al-Su ʿadāʾ -- t1 The Khānqāh -- t2 The Sufis of the Khānqāh -- t3 What is Popular about the Khānqāh? -- tPART TWO State-sanctioned Sufism: The Nascent Shādhilīya -- t4 The Emergence of the Shādhilīya in Egypt -- t5 Al-Iskandarī’s Image of the Shādhilī Tarīqa -- t6 The Popularisation of Shādhilī Sufism -- tPART THREE Unruly Sufism: The Sufis of Upper Egypt -- t7 The Regional Context of Upper-Egyptian Sufism -- t8 Sufi Activists and Enforcers -- t9 Wonder-working Sufis -- tConcluding Remarks -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA social, political and religious history of Sufism in Medieval EgyptAfter the fall of the Fatimid Empire in 1171 and the emergence of a new Sunni polity under the Ayyubids, Sufism came to extraordinary prominence in Egypt. The state founded and funded hospices to attract foreign Sufis to Egypt; local charismatic Sufi masters appeared throughout Upper and Lower Egypt; organised Sufi brotherhoods emerged in the urban centres of Cairo and Alexandria; and even Jews took up the doctrines and practices of the Sufis. By the middle of the Mamluk period in the 14th century, Sufism had become massively popular. How and why did this popularisation happen? This book is the first to address this issue directly, surveying the social formation and histories of several different Sufi collectivities from this period. Arguing that the popularisation of Sufism during this time was the direct result of deliberate and variegated Sufi programs of outreach, strategies of legitimation and performances of authority across Egypt, these programs, strategies and performances are situated within the social and political contexts of the institutionalisation of Sufism, audience participation, and Ayyubid and Mamluk state policies.Key FeaturesOffers a wide-ranging description of the variegated social landscape of Sufism in Ayyubid and early Mamluk EgyptPresents a new theoretical model to describe the institutionalisation and popularisation of SufismCase studies of three different groups of Sufis in medieval Egypt track this institutionalisation and popularisationA heuristic framework connects Sufism to larger social and political trends in medieval Egypt  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMysticismxIslamzEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSufismzEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSufismzEgyptxHistory. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078045140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748694228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748694228/original  a978-3-11-078045-1  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aE